rdf:Description.cw:cwrcInfo: {"nameType":"place","id":"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cottam,_East_Riding_of_Yorkshire","uri":"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cottam,_East_Riding_of_Yorkshire","uriForDisplay":"https://dbpedia.lookup.services.cwrc.ca/resource/Cottam,_East_Riding_of_Yorkshire","name":"Cottam, East Riding of Yorkshire","repository":"dbpedia","originalQueryString":"Cottam","description":"Cottam is a hamlet and civil parish in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England. It is situated on the Yorkshire Wolds approximately 3 miles (4.8 km) east of the village of Sledmere. It lies west of the B1249 road. The civil parish is formed by the hamlets of Cottam and Cowlam. According to the 2001 UK census, Cottam parish had a population of 74, which is the lowest population figure of any East Riding of Yorkshire civil parish in 2001."}

{"nameType":"place","id":"http://dbpedia.org/resource/City_of_London","uri":"http://dbpedia.org/resource/City_of_London","uriForDisplay":"https://dbpedia.lookup.services.cwrc.ca/resource/City_of_London","name":"City of London","repository":"dbpedia","originalQueryString":"London","description":"The City of London is an area in central London, England. In the medieval period it constituted most of London, but the conurbation has grown far beyond it. As the City’s boundaries have remained almost unchanged since the Middle Ages, it is now only a tiny part of the metropolis, though it remains a notable part of central London, holds city status in its own right, and is a separate ceremonial county."}

{"nameType":"place","id":"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leeds,_Kent","uri":"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Leeds,_Kent","uriForDisplay":"https://dbpedia.lookup.services.cwrc.ca/resource/Leeds,_Kent","name":"Leeds, Kent","repository":"dbpedia","originalQueryString":"Leeds, Kent","description":"Leeds is a village and civil parish in the Maidstone District of Kent, England. The parish is located to the east of Maidstone. The village of Leeds is five miles (8 km) from the county town. It appeared in the Domesday Book of 1086 called Esledes - an old English word meaning slope or hillside. It is so called because the village is on the hillside above the River Len, a tributary of the River Medway."}

projectDesc.p: Records of Early English Drama (REED) is an international scholarly project that is establishing for the first time the context from which the drama of Shakespeare and his contemporaries grew. Founded in 1976, REED has worked since then to locate, transcribe, and edit historical documents containing evidence of drama, secular music, and other communal entertainment and ceremony from the Middle Ages until 1642, when the Puritans closed the London theatres.

mods:mods.mods:abstract: Uniquely among Inns of Court admissions registers, the Gray’s Inn Admittance Book contains admissions entries signed by its Christmas prince, the ‘Prince of Purpoole’ (see pp 124–5, 200–1). The standard essential publication is Joseph Foster (ed), The Register of Admissions to Gray’s Inn, 1521–1889, together with the Register of Marriages in Gray’s Inn Chapel, 1695–1754 (London, 1889).
